04541nam a22005895i 9780804767774DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222006cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047677747 a10.1515/97808047677742doi  a(DE-B1597)582421  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aHIS0070002bisacsh1 aReeves, René, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLadinos with Ladinos, Indians with Indians :bLand, Labor, and Regional Ethnic Conflict in the Making of Guatemala /cRené Reeves. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b5 tables, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Rewriting Guatemala$ Nineteenth Century -- t1. The Transformation of Mam Quezaltenango from Culaha to Independence -- t2. Disputing Property: National Politics and Local Ethnic Conflict in the Formation of a Guatemalan Coffee Zone -- t3. Debt, Labor Coercion, and the Expansion of Commercial Agriculture -- t4. Intoxicating Politics: Gender, Ethnicity, and Alcohol in the Transition to Liberal Rule -- t5. From Ladino State to Ladino Nation: The Malformation of Guatemalan National Identity -- t6. Popular Insurrection, Liberal Reform, and Nation-State Formation: Final Reflections on Guatemala's Nineteenth Century -- tNotes and Abbreviations -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late 1830s an uprising of mestizos and Maya destroyed Guatemala's Liberal government for imposing reforms aimed at expanding the state, assimilating indigenous peoples, and encouraging commercial agriculture. Liberal partisans were unable to retake the state until 1871, but after they did they successfully implemented their earlier reform agenda. In contrast to the late 1830s, they met only sporadic resistance. Reeves confronts this paradox of Guatemala's nineteenth century by focusing on the rural folk of the western highlands. He links the area of study to the national level in an explicitly comparative enterprise, unlike most investigations of Mesoamerican communities. He finds that changes in land, labor, and ethnic politics from the 1840s to the 1870s left popular sectors unwilling or unable to mount a repeat of the earlier anti-Liberal mobilization. Because of these changes, the Liberals of the 1870s and beyond consolidated their hold on power more successfully than their counterparts of the 1830s. Ultimately, Reeves shows that community politics and regional ethnic tensions were the crucible of nation-state formation in nineteenth-century Guatemala.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEthnic conflictzGuatemalaxHistory. 0aLadino (Latin American people)xLand tenurezGuatemala. 0aLadino (Latin American people)zGuatemalaxEthnic identity. 0aLadino (Latin American people)zGuatemalaxPolitics and government. 0aLand reformzGuatemalaxHistory. 0aMayasxLand tenurezGuatemala. 0aMayaszGuatemalaxEthnic identity. 0aMayaszGuatemalaxPolitics and government. 0aSocial problemszGuatemalaxHistory. 0aTelevision in educationzAmerican Samoa. 4aHistory -- Latin American. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Central America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107042040 cprintz978080475213840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804767774?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804767774423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804767774/original  a978-3-11-070420-4  Stanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles